China does change, but usually chaotically, and the result of the chaos is always another dictatorship. A glance at China's history will reveal more than a hundred major revolutions and revolts. We hear about the big ones like the Boxer Rebellion and Communist Revolution but others are less well-known, such as the Taiping rebellion. The Taiping Rebellion was led by Hong Xiaquan. He claimed to be Jesus's brother. He was accompanied in his campaigns by a bevy of silk-clad maidens. He slaughtered the inhabitants of every town and village he conquered on the way to Beijing, and was only stopped at the last moment by General "Chinese" Gordon, an Englishman commanding Chinese Imperial Troops. The death toll is thought to be in excess of 20 million. More recently Mao Zedong caused the death of 40 million in his "Great Leap Forward". So let's hope that when China does change, it won't follow precedent.



